Title: A Christmas Carol
Credit: Written by
Author: Charles Dickens
Source: Adapted from book
Draft date: 12/20/2025
Notes: Period Victorian live-action; fogbound London; grounded costumes and faces — no cartoon rendering. Scrooge: elderly, spare, pointed nose, thin blue lips, frosty wiry chin, threadbare black frock coat. Bob Cratchit: thin, threadbare, white comforter. Fred: young, ruddy, handsome, glowing from cold. Marley: dead partner in waistcoat and cash-boxes, transparent, jaw bound. Ghost of Christmas Present: jovial giant, green robe, holly wreath, bare breast and feet, rusted empty scabbard.

===

EXT. LONDON STREET - CHRISTMAS EVE - DAY

Fog and biting cold. City clocks. Candles flare in windows like ruddy smears on brown air. People stamp and beat their hands. A warehouse sign reads: SCROOGE AND MARLEY.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Marley was dead: to begin with. There is no doubt whatever about that. Old Marley was as dead as a door-nail. Scrooge knew he was dead? Of course he did.

INT. SCROOGE'S COUNTING-HOUSE - DAY

A mean room. EBENEZER SCROOGE, elderly, hard and sharp as flint, pointed nose, thin blue lips, frosty rime on eyebrows and wiry chin, black frock coat, hunches over ledgers at a very small fire. The door stands open to a dismal little cell beyond.

In the Tank, BOB CRATCHIT, thin, cold, in a white comforter, copies letters at a fire that looks like one coal. He warms his hands at his candle and fails.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Oh! But he was a tight-fisted hand at the grind-stone, Scrooge! a squeezing, wrenching, grasping, scraping, clutching, covetous, old sinner. He carried his own low temperature always about with him.

The outer door bursts open. FRED, Scrooge's nephew — young, ruddy, handsome, eyes sparkling, breath smoking — comes in all in a glow.

FRED
A merry Christmas, uncle! God save you!

SCROOGE
Bah! Humbug!

FRED
Christmas a humbug, uncle! You don't mean that, I am sure?

SCROOGE
I do. Merry Christmas! What right have you to be merry? What reason have you to be merry? You're poor enough.

FRED
Come, then. What right have you to be dismal? What reason have you to be morose? You're rich enough.

SCROOGE
Bah! Humbug!

FRED
Don't be cross, uncle!

SCROOGE
What else can I be, when I live in such a world of fools as this? Merry Christmas! Out upon merry Christmas! What's Christmas time to you but a time for paying bills without money; a time for finding yourself a year older, but not an hour richer; a time for balancing your books and having every item in 'em through a round dozen of months presented dead against you? If I could work my will, every idiot who goes about with "Merry Christmas" on his lips, should be boiled with his own pudding, and buried with a stake of holly through his heart. He should!

FRED
Uncle!

SCROOGE
Nephew! Keep Christmas in your own way, and let me keep it in mine.

FRED
Keep it! But you don't keep it.

SCROOGE
Let me leave it alone, then. Much good may it do you! Much good it has ever done you!

FRED
There are many things from which I might have derived good, by which I have not profited, I dare say. Christmas among the rest. But I am sure I have always thought of Christmas time, when it has come round — as a good time; a kind, forgiving, charitable, pleasant time; the only time I know of, in the long calendar of the year, when men and women seem by one consent to open their shut-up hearts freely, and to think of people below them as if they really were fellow-passengers to the grave, and not another race of creatures bound on other journeys. And therefore, uncle, though it has never put a scrap of gold or silver in my pocket, I believe that it has done me good, and will do me good; and I say, God bless it!

In the Tank, Bob involuntarily applauds — then, sensible of the impropriety, pokes his fire and extinguishes the last frail spark.

SCROOGE
Let me hear another sound from you, and you'll keep your Christmas by losing your situation! You're quite a powerful speaker, sir. I wonder you don't go into Parliament.

FRED
Don't be angry, uncle. Come! Dine with us to-morrow.

SCROOGE
I'll see you in that extremity first.

FRED
But why?

SCROOGE
Why did you get married?

FRED
Because I fell in love.

SCROOGE
Because you fell in love! Good afternoon!

FRED
Nay, uncle, but you never came to see me before that happened. Why give it as a reason for not coming now?

SCROOGE
Good afternoon.

FRED
I want nothing from you; I ask nothing of you; why cannot we be friends?

SCROOGE
Good afternoon.

FRED
I am sorry, with all my heart, to find you so resolute. We have never had any quarrel, to which I have been a party. But I have made the trial in homage to Christmas, and I'll keep my Christmas humour to the last. So A Merry Christmas, uncle!

SCROOGE
Good afternoon!

FRED
And A Happy New Year!

SCROOGE
Good afternoon!

Fred leaves without an angry word. At the outer door he bestows the greetings of the season on Bob, who returns them cordially.

SCROOGE
(muttering)
There's another fellow — my clerk, with fifteen shillings a week, and a wife and family, talking about a merry Christmas. I'll retire to Bedlam.

As Fred goes out, two PORTLY GENTLEMEN enter, pleasant to behold, hats off, books and papers in hand. They bow.

PORTLY GENTLEMAN
Scrooge and Marley's, I believe. Have I the pleasure of addressing Mr. Scrooge, or Mr. Marley?

SCROOGE
Mr. Marley has been dead these seven years. He died seven years ago, this very night.

PORTLY GENTLEMAN
We have no doubt his liberality is well represented by his surviving partner. At this festive season of the year, Mr. Scrooge, it is more than usually desirable that we should make some slight provision for the Poor and Destitute, who suffer greatly at the present time. Many thousands are in want of common necessaries; hundreds of thousands are in want of common comforts, sir.

SCROOGE
Are there no prisons?

PORTLY GENTLEMAN
Plenty of prisons.

SCROOGE
And the Union workhouses? Are they still in operation?

PORTLY GENTLEMAN
They are. Still. I wish I could say they were not.

SCROOGE
The Treadmill and the Poor Law are in full vigour, then?

PORTLY GENTLEMAN
Both very busy, sir.

SCROOGE
Oh! I was afraid, from what you said at first, that something had occurred to stop them in their useful course. I'm very glad to hear it.

PORTLY GENTLEMAN
Under the impression that they scarcely furnish Christian cheer of mind or body to the multitude, a few of us are endeavouring to raise a fund to buy the Poor some meat and drink, and means of warmth. What shall I put you down for?

SCROOGE
Nothing!

PORTLY GENTLEMAN
You wish to be anonymous?

SCROOGE
I wish to be left alone. Since you ask me what I wish, gentlemen, that is my answer. I don't make merry myself at Christmas and I can't afford to make idle people merry. I help to support the establishments I have mentioned — they cost enough; and those who are badly off must go there.

PORTLY GENTLEMAN
Many can't go there; and many would rather die.

SCROOGE
If they would rather die, they had better do it, and decrease the surplus population. Besides — it's not my business. It's enough for a man to understand his own business, and not to interfere with other people's. Mine occupies me constantly. Good afternoon, gentlemen!

The gentlemen withdraw. Fog presses at the panes. Scrooge returns to his work. Bob tries again to warm himself.

EXT. COUNTING-HOUSE DOOR - NIGHT

Closing time. Scrooge buttons his coat to the chin. Bob hovers, hopeful.

SCROOGE
You'll want all day to-morrow, I suppose?

BOB CRATCHIT
If quite convenient, sir.

SCROOGE
It's not convenient, and it's not fair. If I was to stop half-a-crown for it, you'd think yourself ill-used, I'll be bound?

Bob smiles faintly.

SCROOGE
And yet you don't think me ill-used, when I pay a day's wages for no work.

BOB CRATCHIT
It's only once a year, sir.

SCROOGE
A poor excuse for picking a man's pocket every twenty-fifth of December! But I suppose you must have the whole day. Be here all the earlier next morning.

Bob promises and flees into the fog, sliding on ice with other boys in pure delight. Scrooge locks up and walks home alone through the narrow court.

EXT. SCROOGE'S HOUSE - NIGHT

A gloomy suite of rooms in a lowering building. Scrooge approaches his door. The knocker — ordinary iron — for an instant becomes JACOB MARLEY's face: dead, spectral, eyes wide.

Scrooge stares. The face is a knocker again. He turns the key, checks the back of the door, and goes in.

INT. SCROOGE'S CHAMBERS - NIGHT

Dark sitting-room. Small fire. Scrooge double-locks himself in, puts on his dressing-gown, slippers, and nightcap, and takes gruel by the hearth.

Bells in the house begin to ring — then stop. A chain clanks in the cellar and climbs the stairs.

SCROOGE
Humbug!

The sitting-room door flies open. MARLEY'S GHOST enters: same face as the knocker, transparent, in waistcoat, tights, and boots; a heavy chain wound about him, made of cash-boxes, keys, padlocks, ledgers, deeds, and heavy purses. His jaw is bound up with a cloth.

SCROOGE
How now! What do you want with me?

MARLEY
Much!

SCROOGE
Who are you?

MARLEY
Ask me who I was.

SCROOGE
Who were you then?

MARLEY
In life I was your partner, Jacob Marley.

SCROOGE
Can you — can you sit down?

MARLEY
I can.

Marley sits in the chair across the fire. The flame leaps as if glad of company.

SCROOGE
You don't believe in me.

SCROOGE
I don't.

MARLEY
Why do you doubt your senses?

SCROOGE
Because a little thing affects them. A slight disorder of the stomach makes them cheats. You may be an undigested bit of beef, a blot of mustard, a crumb of cheese, a fragment of an underdone potato. There's more of gravy than of grave about you, whatever you are!

Marley raises a frightful cry and shakes his chain. Scrooge clings to his chair. Marley takes the bandage from his jaw; the lower jaw drops upon his breast. Scrooge falls to his knees.

SCROOGE
Mercy! Dreadful apparition, why do you trouble me?

MARLEY
Man of the worldly mind! Do you believe in me or not?

SCROOGE
I do. I must. But why do spirits walk the earth, and why do they come to me?

MARLEY
It is required of every man that the spirit within him should walk abroad among his fellowmen, and travel far and wide; and if that spirit goes not forth in life, it is condemned to do so after death. I cannot rest, I cannot stay, I cannot linger anywhere. My spirit never walked beyond our counting-house — mark me! — in life my spirit never roved beyond the narrow limits of our money-changing hole; and weary journeys lie before me!

SCROOGE
You are fettered. Tell me why.

MARLEY
I wear the chain I forged in life. I made it link by link, and yard by yard. Is its pattern strange to you? Or would you know the weight and length of the strong coil you bear yourself? It was full as heavy and as long as this, seven Christmas Eves ago. You have laboured on it, since. It is a ponderous chain!

SCROOGE
Jacob. Old Jacob Marley, tell me more. Speak comfort to me, Jacob!

MARLEY
I have none to give. I cannot stay; I cannot linger anywhere. That I am here to-night is a chance and hope of my own procuring, Ebenezer. You will be haunted by Three Spirits.

SCROOGE
I — I think I'd rather not.

MARLEY
Without their visits, you cannot hope to shun the path I tread. Expect the first to-morrow, when the bell tolls One. Expect the second on the next night at the same hour. The third upon the next night when the last stroke of Twelve has ceased to vibrate. Look to see me no more. For your own sake, remember what has passed between us!

Marley winds the bandage round his jaw. He rises, trails his chain to the window. The sash rises of itself. Outside, the air is filled with phantoms, fettered, wailing, many once known to Scrooge — one wretched ghost cries at a poor woman with an infant, unable to help. Marley joins them and is gone. The night is clear again.

Scrooge tries to say Humbug — cannot. He stumbles to bed without undressing.

INT. SCROOGE'S BEDROOM - NIGHT

The bell tolls One. Light flashes. A spirit stands at the bedcurtains: like a child and like an old man; long white hair; face without wrinkle; white tunic; a branch of fresh green holly; a cap under its arm; a jet of light springs from its head.

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PAST
I am the Ghost of Christmas Past. Rise! and walk with me!

Scrooge takes the Spirit's hand. They pass through the wall.

EXT. COUNTRY ROAD / SCHOOL / FEZZIWIG'S WAREHOUSE - NIGHT (VISION)

Quick, clear visions as they fly:

A lonely boy left at a boarding school at Christmas — young Scrooge — reading alone while other boys go home.

A younger Scrooge, apprenticed, dancing at fat jolly FEZZIWIG's Christmas ball: fiddles, roast meats, the apprentices whirling, Fezziwig clapping as if his private power could make a world of joy with a few pounds.

A fair young woman, BELLE, releasing younger Scrooge from their engagement in a bare room.

BELLE
Another idol has displaced me. A golden one. May you be happy in the life you have chosen.

Older Belle now, married, her home full of laughing children; her husband speaks of passing Scrooge's office — quite alone in the world. Scrooge cannot bear it.

SCROOGE
Spirit! Show me no more! Conduct me home. Why do you delight to torture me? Remove me from this place!

He seizes the Spirit's cap and presses it down upon the light. He is in his own bedroom again, exhausted, and sinks upon the bed.

INT. SCROOGE'S CHAMBERS - NIGHT

He wakes to a blaze of light from the adjoining room. He rises in his dressing-gown and approaches the door.

INT. SCROOGE'S SITTING-ROOM - NIGHT

The room is transformed: leaves of holly, mistletoe, and ivy; a throne of turkeys, geese, game, poultry, brawn, pigs, sausages, oysters, pies, puddings, fruit, and punch. Upon the couch sits the GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT — a jovial giant, glorious to see: green robe bordered with white fur, bare breast, bare feet, dark brown curls free, holly wreath set with shining icicles, antique scabbard empty and rusted at his side, open hand, sparkling eye, cheery voice. A glowing torch rests by him.

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
You have never seen the like of me before!

SCROOGE
Never.

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
Have never walked forth with the younger members of my family; meaning (for I am very young) my elder brothers born in these later years?

SCROOGE
I don't think I have. I am afraid I have not. Have you had many brothers, Spirit?

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
More than eighteen hundred.

SCROOGE
A tremendous family to provide for!

The Ghost of Christmas Present rises.

SCROOGE
Spirit, conduct me where you will. I went forth last night on compulsion, and I learnt a lesson which is working now. To-night, if you have aught to teach me, let me profit by it.

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
Touch my robe!

Scrooge holds it fast.

EXT. LONDON STREETS - CHRISTMAS MORNING - DAY

Holly, mistletoe, room, fire, and night vanish. They stand in the city streets on Christmas morning. Severe weather. People scrape snow from pavement and housetops; boys shout with mad delight as snow plumps into the road in artificial little snow-storms.

House fronts black against white roofs; yellow mud and icy water in the furrows of cart-wheels; dingy mist and sooty atoms. Yet cheerfulness abroad. Neighbours call from parapets and exchange facetious snowballs, laughing whether right or wrong.

Poulterers' shops half open; fruiterers radiant — baskets of chestnuts, Spanish onions, pears and apples in pyramids, grapes dangling, filberts, Norfolk Biffins, oranges and lemons. Grocers nearly closed, but through the gaps: merry scales, brisk twine, rattling canisters, tea and coffee, raisins, almonds, cinnamon, candied fruits. Customers tumble against each other in the best humour possible.

Steeples call good people to church and chapel. From bye-streets, innumerable people carry their dinners to the bakers' shops. The Spirit stands with Scrooge in a baker's doorway and, taking off the covers as bearers pass, sprinkles incense on their dinners from his torch. When angry words rise between dinner-carriers who have jostled, he sheds a few drops from the torch; good humour is restored.

DINNER-CARRIER
It was a shame to quarrel upon Christmas Day.

ANOTHER VOICE
And so it was! God love it, so it was!

Bells cease. Bakers shut. Thawed blotches of wet smoke above each oven.

SCROOGE
Is there a peculiar flavour in what you sprinkle from your torch?

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
There is. My own.

SCROOGE
Would it apply to any kind of dinner on this day?

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
To any kindly given. To a poor one most.

SCROOGE
Why to a poor one most?

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
Because it needs it most.

SCROOGE
Spirit, I wonder you, of all the beings in the many worlds about us, should desire to cramp these people's opportunities of innocent enjoyment. You would deprive them of their means of dining every seventh day, often the only day on which they can be said to dine at all—

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
I!

The Spirit's eyes flash. Scrooge lowers his gaze, chastened. The torch dips toward a narrow street.

EXT. CAMDEN TOWN / INT. CRATCHIT HOME - DAY

A small four-roomed house. BOB CRATCHIT comes home in his comforter, carrying TINY TIM upon his shoulder — a little crippled boy with an iron frame, clear voice, and a little crutch. MRS. CRATCHIT, brave in a twice-turned gown and ribbon, greets them with the elder children: BELINDA, PETER, and the two smaller Cratchits.

They bustle about a meagre goose, sage and onion, applesauce, mashed potatoes, and a Christmas pudding blazing with scant brandy. Bob toasts with hot mixture from a jug.

BOB CRATCHIT
A Merry Christmas to us all, my dears. God bless us!

TINY TIM
God bless us every one!

Bob holds Tim's withered hand. Scrooge watches, stricken.

SCROOGE
Spirit, tell me if Tiny Tim will live.

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
I see a vacant seat in the poor chimney-corner, and a crutch without an owner, carefully preserved. If these shadows remain unaltered by the Future, the child will die.

SCROOGE
No, no. Oh, no, kind Spirit! say he will be spared.

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
If these shadows remain unaltered by the Future, none other of my race will find him here. What then? If he be like to die, he had better do it, and decrease the surplus population.

Scrooge hangs his head at the hearing of his own words. Bob's voice rises again in the little room, full of love for Tim. The Spirit draws Scrooge away.

EXT. STREETS AND FRED'S HOUSE - NIGHT (MONTAGE)

The Spirit shows miners, lighthouse keepers, shipmen at sea — all keeping Christmas with song. Then Fred's bright parlour: Fred, his pretty wife, Topper, and friends laugh over games; Fred toasts his uncle kindly despite the humbug, hoping the old man may think better. Scrooge begins to join the games in spirit, then the scene fades.

The Ghost grows older as the night wears — his hair grey. At last, from beneath his robe, two wretched children cling: a boy and girl, wolfish, meagre — Ignorance and Want.

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
Beware them both, and all of their degree, but most of all beware this boy, for on his brow I see that written which is Doom, unless the writing be erased.

SCROOGE
Have they no refuge or resource?

GHOST OF CHRISTMAS PRESENT
Are there no prisons? Are there no workhouses?

The bell strikes Twelve. The Ghost is gone. Scrooge sees a solemn PHANTOM, draped and hooded in black, approaching like a mist along the ground — the GHOST OF CHRISTMAS YET TO COME. It does not speak. It only points.

EXT. CITY / EXCHANGE / DARK STREETS - NIGHT (VISION)

Silent visions under the Phantom's finger:

Business men in the Exchange shrug over a death — "When did he die?" — "Last night, I believe." — No one mourns; one will go to the funeral if lunch is provided.

A filthy rag-and-bottle shop where a charwoman, a laundress, and an undertaker's man sell bedcurtains, blankets, and the shirt off a corpse's back — plunder from a man who died alone.

A body on a stripped bed, face covered, unwatched, unwept.

A poor couple granted a cruel breathing-space because their pitiless creditor is dead.

Then the Cratchit home again: quiet, hushed. Bob returns from the churchyard. Tiny Tim's little crutch is still. Bob breaks down, then steadies for his family — Tim was good and kind.

Bob's voice, soft:

BOB CRATCHIT
I am sure we shall none of us forget poor Tiny Tim — shall we — or this first parting that there was among us?

The Phantom points to a neglected churchyard. A neglected grave. Scrooge resists, then forces himself to read the stone:

EBENEZER SCROOGE.

SCROOGE
No, Spirit! Oh no, no! Spirit! hear me! I am not the man I was. I will not be the man I must have been but for this intercourse. Why show me this, if I am past all hope! Assure me that I yet may change these shadows you have shown me, by an altered life!

He clutches the spectral hand. The Phantom shrinks, collapses — becomes a bedpost.

INT. SCROOGE'S BEDROOM - MORNING

Daylight. Soft bedcurtains. Scrooge clings to his own bedpost, gasping — then laughs and weeps at once.

SCROOGE
I will live in the Past, the Present, and the Future. The Spirits of all Three shall strive within me. Oh Jacob Marley! Heaven, and the Christmas Time be praised for this! I say it on my knees, old Jacob; on my knees!

He scrambles out of bed, runs to the window, opens it. Church bells ring out, glorious. Cold, bright, stirring day.

SCROOGE
What's to-day?

He calls down to a BOY in Sunday clothes below in the street.

BOY
Eh?

SCROOGE
What's to-day, my fine fellow?

BOY
To-day! Why, CHRISTMAS DAY.

SCROOGE
It's Christmas Day! I haven't missed it. The Spirits have done it all in one night. They can do anything they like. Of course they can. Hallo, my fine fellow!

BOY
Hallo!

SCROOGE
Do you know the Poulterer's, in the next street but one, at the corner?

BOY
I should hope I did.

SCROOGE
An intelligent boy! A remarkable boy! Do you know whether they've sold the prize Turkey that was hanging up there? — Not the little prize Turkey: the big one?

BOY
What, the one as big as me?

SCROOGE
What a delightful boy! It's a pleasure to talk to him. Yes, my buck!

BOY
It's hanging there now.

SCROOGE
Is it? Go and buy it.

BOY
Walk-ER!

SCROOGE
No, no, I am in earnest. Go and buy it, and tell 'em to bring it here, that I may give them the direction where to take it. Come back with the man, and I'll give you a shilling. Come back with him in less than five minutes and I'll give you half-a-crown!

The boy is off like a shot.

SCROOGE
(whispering, rubbing his hands)
I'll send it to Bob Cratchit's! He sha'n't know who sends it. It's twice the size of Tiny Tim. Joe Miller never made such a joke as sending it to Bob's will be!

He writes the address with an unsteady hand, goes downstairs, and opens the street door. The knocker catches his eye. He pats it.

SCROOGE
I shall love it, as long as I live! I scarcely ever looked at it before. What an honest expression it has in its face! It's a wonderful knocker! — Here's the Turkey! Hallo! Whoop! How are you! Merry Christmas!

EXT. SCROOGE'S DOORSTEP - DAY

A vast Turkey arrives — too big to have stood upon its legs. Scrooge chuckles, pays for the bird, pays for a cab to Camden Town, recompenses the boy, and chuckles till he cries.

INT. SCROOGE'S CHAMBERS - DAY

Shaving is hard; his hand shakes. He dresses all in his best and goes out into the streets.

EXT. LONDON STREETS - DAY

People pour forth as he saw them with the Ghost of Christmas Present. Scrooge walks with hands behind him, regarding everyone with a delighted smile. Good-humoured fellows greet him.

PASSERSBY
Good morning, sir! A merry Christmas to you!

SCROOGE
(beaming)
And a merry Christmas to you!

He has not gone far when he meets the PORTLY GENTLEMAN who came to the counting-house the day before. A pang crosses Scrooge's heart — then he quickens his pace and takes both the gentleman's hands.

SCROOGE
My dear sir, how do you do? I hope you succeeded yesterday. It was very kind of you. A merry Christmas to you, sir!

PORTLY GENTLEMAN
Mr. Scrooge?

SCROOGE
Yes. That is my name, and I fear it may not be pleasant to you. Allow me to ask your pardon. And will you have the goodness—

He whispers in the gentleman's ear.

PORTLY GENTLEMAN
Lord bless me! My dear Mr. Scrooge, are you serious?

SCROOGE
If you please. Not a farthing less. A great many back-payments are included in it, I assure you. Will you do me that favour?

PORTLY GENTLEMAN
My dear sir, I don't know what to say to such munifi—

SCROOGE
Don't say anything, please. Come and see me. Will you come and see me?

PORTLY GENTLEMAN
I will!

SCROOGE
Thank'ee. I am much obliged to you. I thank you fifty times. Bless you!

Scrooge goes to church, walks the streets, pats children on the head, questions beggars, looks down into kitchens and up to windows — everything yields him pleasure.

EXT. FRED'S HOUSE - AFTERNOON

He passes the door a dozen times, then makes a dash and knocks. A pleasant GIRL opens.

SCROOGE
Is your master at home, my dear?

GIRL
Yes, sir.

SCROOGE
Where is he, my love?

GIRL
He's in the dining-room, sir, along with mistress. I'll show you up-stairs, if you please.

SCROOGE
Thank'ee. He knows me. I'll go in here, my dear.

INT. FRED'S DINING-ROOM - AFTERNOON

The table is spread in great array. Fred and his wife look it over. Scrooge sidles his face in round the door.

SCROOGE
Fred!

Fred's wife starts. Fred turns.

FRED
Why bless my soul! Who's that?

SCROOGE
It's I. Your uncle Scrooge. I have come to dinner. Will you let me in, Fred?

Fred nearly shakes his arm off. In five minutes Scrooge is at home. Hearty welcome. Niece the same; Topper; the plump sister; everyone. Wonderful party, wonderful games, wonderful happiness.

INT. SCROOGE'S COUNTING-HOUSE - NEXT MORNING

Scrooge is early — door wide open to the Tank — set upon catching Bob coming late. The clock strikes nine. No Bob. A quarter past. No Bob. Eighteen minutes and a half behind his time.

Bob rushes in, hat and comforter off, on his stool in a jiffy, driving with his pen as if to overtake nine o'clock.

SCROOGE
(growling, feigning the old voice)
Hallo! What do you mean by coming here at this time of day?

BOB CRATCHIT
I am very sorry, sir. I am behind my time.

SCROOGE
You are? Yes. I think you are. Step this way, sir, if you please.

BOB CRATCHIT
It's only once a year, sir. It shall not be repeated. I was making rather merry yesterday, sir.

SCROOGE
Now, I'll tell you what, my friend. I am not going to stand this sort of thing any longer. And therefore—

He leaps from his stool and digs Bob in the waistcoat so that Bob staggers back into the Tank.

SCROOGE
And therefore I am about to raise your salary!

Bob trembles, edges nearer the ruler — a momentary idea of knocking Scrooge down and calling for a strait-waistcoat.

SCROOGE
A merry Christmas, Bob! A merrier Christmas, Bob, my good fellow, than I have given you, for many a year! I'll raise your salary, and endeavour to assist your struggling family, and we will discuss your affairs this very afternoon, over a Christmas bowl of smoking bishop, Bob! Make up the fires, and buy another coal-scuttle before you dot another i, Bob Cratchit!

Bob stares — then joy breaks over his face as Scrooge claps him on the back in earnest kindness.

EXT. LONDON / CRATCHIT HOME - DAY (MONTAGE)

NARRATOR (V.O.)
Scrooge was better than his word. He did it all, and infinitely more; and to Tiny Tim, who did NOT die, he was a second father.

Scrooge at the Cratchit hearth with Tim upon his knee; Scrooge laughing in the streets; Scrooge at the office fire with Bob, coal-scuttle full; people smiling at the alteration in him — some laughing; Scrooge letting them laugh, his own heart laughing enough for him.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
He became as good a friend, as good a master, and as good a man, as the good old city knew, or any other good old city, town, or borough, in the good old world. He had no further intercourse with Spirits, but lived upon the Total Abstinence Principle, ever afterwards; and it was always said of him, that he knew how to keep Christmas well, if any man alive possessed the knowledge. May that be truly said of us, and all of us!

INT. CRATCHIT HOME - EVENING

Tiny Tim, alive and bright, looks up amid the family and Scrooge.

TINY TIM
God bless Us, Every One!

FADE OUT.

THE END
